Architects have understood that offices also need guardianship
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say it hides also inside a small gardener with everything in its own to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of the employees of Arch.Design can attend it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose study numerous well-known buildings from Brno came out, thought from the early sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its miniguardery.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly in the baby boom age and wanted to allow architects and delineators to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced time, the gardenery is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers its workers within the framework of its social program.
Constructors and architects in this way have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with the care of the children.
The miniguardery was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s miniguardian is funded through the European Social Fund in the framework of the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a donation of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they could buy equipment and, after two years, hire qualified staff and services.
When funding is exhausted (two years), the company Arch.Design has the obligation to keep the miniguardery in operation with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the funding application.
Children’s care is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The nurse currently welcomes children without age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it’s a “minority”, it can only accommodate simultaneously a maximum of five children, although with the turns they go more during the day.
The operation of the nurse is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nurse, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the childhood program are comparable to the usual pre-school teaching program.
In it children not only play, but also receive a quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, teaching to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of small children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking late school children when they are far from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is placed among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, in the end, this program strengthened staff marketing.
The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years.
The roof looks like the lame of a prehistoric slope, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals named it "the house of the bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the new use of the stone, the fragments of blacks and mosaics, a façade that reminds of the scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of Antoni Gaudí’s secession.
The cover of the house plays with onyrial lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
By paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought order is observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, as it is illuminated so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
The serpent and the tortion of the shapes continue to surprise us also inside.
The wave wood copies the frames of the windows, the bars, the doors of the doors, the mirillas and the bridges.
The Casa Batlló, which is located in the neighborhood of Eixample in the number 43 of the animated shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, arose from the remodeling of a house of the year 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on destroying the previous building and starting from zero, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of carrying out a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, formed by various apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
It was designed by architect Josep María Jujol.
In fact, in their plans of the project arose adorns for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the façade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Park Güell de Gaudí, in which other pieces of the same are found.
Due to its organic shape, the locals shortly after its completion named it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of the busts".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, pattern of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating era with ventilation respirators and typical chemines.
It can be strange its 45 degrees inclination.
During the construction, Gaudí did not comply with the construction rules of the moment and did not be influenced by them.
However, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although obviously in it the data indicated about the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the municipality was so impacted with the result that it asked to be corrected.
It disturbed him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public edge.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: just fifteen days after the request of the municipality, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
In the lower floors the owner was installed.
In the gallery of the second floor was the living room and in the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The floor was rented to a jewelry.
The house, six-storey, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted in breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without trouble, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue blacks that cover the inner courtyard and trailers.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on every floor of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb the sun's rays.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and rechargeed apartment of the accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, with the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it’s a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the bakery, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist cards holders get a 20% discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the entrance price of other Gaudí buildings in the city.
