A finger index longer than the canular indicates a lower risk of developing cancer
Men who have the longer index than the cancellation are subject to a lower risk of suffering from prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in a British magazine on cancer.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
“Our findings indicate that the relative length of the finger can be a simple proof of the risk of developing prostate cancer, especially for men up to 60 years old,” said Ros Eeles, co-author of the study, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Consequently, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, if this feature goes associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, according to Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, he carried out the tracking with a British homologist of more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right hand finger shorter than the cancellation.
They presented the same chances of suffering from prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of men with an index longer than the annular finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have shown that testosterone affects the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech genetist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that he doesn’t think that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer can be “totally demonstrated”.
