It continues to increase support for democracy in Latin America, as well as support for private companies.
Crime generates greater concern than unemployment.
Moreover, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a country more influential than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it allows to track the changes in attitude in the region.
In the results of this year’s survey, held in September and early October, two related issues are highlighted.
The first is the relatively animated humor reigning in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
The support for democracy has increased considerably in various countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% annually since 2002, the support for democracy has increased from a reduced 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also grown in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a great decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents from Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which falls the regional average (see chart 2).
Around 44% of respondents in the region declared satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably higher than 25% registered in 2001 (Graph 3).
Around 34% said they trust Congress in their country and 45% in their government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher in relation to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulences in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has beenined during the world financial crisis is probably due to the fact that numerous Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social security network has contributed to protecting the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty just increased marginally in 2009 and that it has decreased again this year, up to 32 percent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s good economic returns and the popularity of its emerging president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and the violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more surveyed in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem their country faces (see chart 5).
Around 31% say they or a close relative have been a victim of the crime in the last year, a figure that has decreased since 38% last year and is the lowest percentage registered since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in greater support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71% of the surveyers in the region claim that private enterprises are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only 56% (see chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela think the same (and 80% support private companies), although their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises a greater leadership in the region, as indicates 19% of the respondents (from 18% last year), followed by the United States (the 9%, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (the 9% against 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered the most influential by the respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
