An arsenic-resistant microbium proposes the possibility of new forms of life on Earth... or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new forms of life on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although researchers have discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it demonstrates that there may be forms of life without the main elements they considered essential.
“This body has a double capacity.”
“It can grow with phosphorus or arsenic.”
“This makes her something very peculiar, although little is missing to be a kind of life really ‘Alien’,” said Paul C. W. Davies of the Arizona State University, co-author of the report that appears in the online edition of Thursday’s Science publication.
For a long time, it has been considered that there are six major essential elements for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, may continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“It makes you wonder what more is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of the Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the discovery is important for the search for life on different planets from Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, know the aspect it has.
The study focuses on a microbium discovered on Earth.
However, the call of a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated a great speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report would indicate the discovery of alien life.
He did not.
What the discovery "so shows is that in other planetary environments, there might be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider indispensable for life may not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
“This work is new because it demonstrates the replacement of one element by another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure,” Cockell added.
The discovery was not done by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrobiology, who directed the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it presents elevated levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so I speculated that a microbium exposed to both could replace one by another.
“Arsenic is mostly toxic because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus.”
"As a result, it may be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
“But the arsenic is different enough so that it doesn’t work as well as the phosphorus, so it enters and, to say somehow, applies the biochemical machinery,” Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt and used to grow.
The microbium grows better with phosphorus, but the fact of demonstrating that it can live with arsenic in its place raises the possibility that it can naturally exist a form of life that uses arsenic, whether in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where the arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, a auxiliary professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic can be replaced with phosphorus is not new, but never found an example that demonstrates that it works.
Arsenic was more common in the early era of Earth, he said, so researchers speculated that the first forms of life could have used it.
“Yes it suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth in ancient times,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
