Can civism stretch a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, a little civism has been triggered this week in Washington.
Is it a prediction of a genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick turn to the party struggle in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders did not produce any advances on the major topics that should be discussed during the coming session.
But for what they all say, it was at least a courtesy discussion about the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, instead of being another empty episode to win party points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the president’s deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the political differences that exist among the members.
It seems clear that the narrow interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
This is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Now both sides are in a period of trial, surveying each other to identify signs of cooperativism and commitment, while trying to evaluate the boundaries of public opinion and voters’ patience for a renewed party war.
The reason for which the meeting on Tuesday and the subsequent evaluations of it by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and are very deeply rooted as to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, health care or social aid, the two parties are in opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the humor in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with respect to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the election.
The elections wake up party passions, which then disappear.
That is good.”
In some issues, in particular those that are listed in the day order of the coming session, Republicans and Democrats have no other option than finding a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts are overcome by the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, it is likely that there will be a commitment to expanding unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans can’t make them believe they’re in favour of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment subsidies for the unemployed workers.
After the meeting on Tuesday at the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these topics during the coming session, along with the ratification of the new nuclear disarmament pact START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston, from the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on the issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to a continued bipartidism when the new 112th Congress is gathered in January.
He said, on the contrary, it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement begins.
“After the things to be done are carried out, in the short term, psychology will turn the situation to one of confrontation,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
For more awareness the Republican leaders have about the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they should try to fulfill their promises of cutting the state expenses and abolishing the new health law.
These party lines are already clearly observed in the initial reactions to the deficit committee’s recommendations, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase of some taxes and the retirement age, and the cut of expenses.
Co-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the hardest jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have brought the issue of deficit into the public day order in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the committee of 18 members to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the chosen officials in the panel, suggesting that in tax issues there is, at least currently, few bases or desire for commitment.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and the Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of party shocks, when the Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and medical care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would the change cause?
the public opinion.
There are considerable evidence that, despite the partyism of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead point, as it happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the people’s reaction.
Anyone who considers that he is losing will probably change course and will seek commitment.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partialism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and it seems that there is a greater ideological hole between Obama and Congress Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as the merely prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization that is shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort from both sides to find points in common in the issues that still divide them.
