Known as "the Carnicer" for his brutality during the Red Jemers government, the commander remains popular in this remote former Red Jemers fortress in northeastern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructures, and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Red Jemers ran before the government, long-established loyalty is finally being challenged at Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed the victims to publicly face the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a secondary school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Red Jemers to the sons of their former soldiers.
And in July, a joint court of the United Nations and Cambodia issued the first conviction of a former member of the Red Jemers, sentencing the former head of the well-known Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of those events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Red Jemers of Anlong Veng, complicating the efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into the Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Red Jemers, but they can’t do anything,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization investigating the regime.
“For them, life under the Red Jemers was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.”
“This is generating divisions within the families.”
During the Government of the Red Jemers of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, illness or excess work.
When in 1979 Vietnamese invaded and defeated the government led by Pol Pot, the remains of the regime and its troops fled to the border of Cambodia with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that rindied in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and forests of Western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the UN led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Red Jemers fighters began to desert towards the government, culminating in Ieng Sary’s surrender in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while waiting for the trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Jemers fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few elite officials of the Red Jemers retained their local administrative positions in exchange for depositing their weapons, the racist soldiers remain poor and unqualified farmers.
“These people have obtained few profits after the surrender,” said Sok Leang from the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They have incorporated the utopian agricultural ideology of the regime.”
“They were raised without any concept to do business.”
Sister Lim, 55 years old, who joined the Red Jemers when he was a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before devoting himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
“Life with the Red Jemers was fine,” he said.
“Ta Mok gave him to eat everyone.”
“But now life is difficult because we have to supply ourselves.”
The current Court of the Red Jemers has also caused concerns here.
At the beginning of next year, the court is expected to begin trial against Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Red Jemer minister.
The court's mandate is to prosecute the main leaders and those of greater responsibility for the crimes, but he has not said if he will pursue cases in addition to those four.
This did not serve much to calm the fears at Anlong Veng.
The recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, a 64-year-old, who was a district leader in the province of Banteay Meanchey during the government of the Red Jemers at the end of the 1970s.
