The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten, but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate arising in the case related is due to the fact that it has been protagonized by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its hymn presumes nobleness and honor, and that in occasions passed has fines its players for analog acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds an episode more to his dilated history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate turns around whether that type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, if with these actions it is committed fraud of law; since, in fact, they are actions respecting the sports regulation, but they seem to elude its meaning.
The question passes by examining the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the goods that sports spirit understands is the physical integrity of the opposite players, aspect that with these actions was not put in danger, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these goods to which it is highlighted with the clean game is to avoid the team of the infringing players to take advantage of the opposite team in an unfair way, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that he did not accommodate what we normally characterize as a trap or fraud of law, since his violation of the rules was not made hidden to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely his action tried to be the most obvious to thus receive the punishment of the arbitrator.
They were waiting and pleasantly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders obtain in the intended faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to constate that the rival is not placed in a disadvantaged situation, nor is it gained in the same match, since obviously the result of the action implies leaving the team with less players.
And this is also not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that can threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, since the team can be eliminated at the first change, and in addition with this action the players meet a sanction match and pass to the second card cycle, in which the suspension by card accumulation occurs with a less than in the first cycle.
So, going through rounds, it’s not so clear that it’s an advantage.
In the end, these actions do not go against the sports spirit, which is part of making strategic decisions that favour the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In the case it occupies us, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without sorting the punishment or escaping from it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law fraud is diffuse, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises by two factors: because it was about two self-expulsions and the way the transmission of the direction of provoking them was carried out.
The damage caused to the sports principles by these actions is not both ethical and aesthetic.
