A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a renewal plan of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GEI) in a amount that corresponds practically to one-third of the additional decrease that should be carried out to stabilize the climate of the planet before 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the set of large concrete projects that the United Nations expects to be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent lamps, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluocompact lamps or, even better, by electroluminescent diodes lamps (DEL or "LED" in English), a large part of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GEI emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitter countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to reduce global GEI emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, there should be a further decrease of 5 Gt of that amount to stabilize, before 2020, the temperature rise by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from being uncontrolled.
In the incandescent lamps, 95% of the energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. a 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact lamps, the energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED lamps, the energy consumption is reduced twice more.
Fluocompact lamps last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED lamps, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week (a company that, in addition, has participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume an 80% less energy than an incandescent lamp, allowing us to make an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in a hundred countries.
These new lamps can also work with reostates and emit very little heat.
They do not contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed their reservations in relation to fluocompact lamps, as they contain mercury and should be removed as dangerous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emission on the planet are not the fluocompact lamps, but the coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is broken with the incandescent lamps.
Only in the United States, these power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international program would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, that is, the equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion dollars.
