Climate: France's chapuses in its financing promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the promises of rapidly unlocked financing (fast start or early) made by developed countries have been met.
The French cappuccino has been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union agreed to contribute €7.2 billion in three years and France €1.260 million (i.e. €420 million per year).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to the fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a great complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation resulted appreciable and was appreciated for what really is worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right path towards the fulfilment of its €7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to the official development aid.
Unfortunately, there has not been an agreement on what it means "new and additional".
When the European Commission proposed a harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Nowadays, each one chooses the reference that best suits him.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference the year 2009: international financing isined and 150 million in three years are added in the concept of fast-start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references as regards the year or the level of official development aid.
France, on the contrary, considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 are "new and additional."
In other words, it does not refer to the expenses of the previous years or the total level of the official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of France’s aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it claims that it respects its commitment to “new and additional” funds.
Another key element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and each chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro borrowed equals one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain profitable investments (often projects related to emission reduction based on more efficient technologies), it is failed to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... As much, it should only be calculated for your commitments the cost of the loan for the country granting the loan (i.e., the equivalent to a rate of interest).
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it “respects” its commitment of 420 million euros making a 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and a 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document to see it by its own eyes.
It is the only country in the EU that uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with a 100% of donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the shares in time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending just 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million “new and additional”, as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has taken over the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States going to continue donating when they can simply borrow?) as well as in negotiations, since developing countries are not foolish...
The chapter of early financing is a thorough, relatively short-term, in relation to the whole of climate negotiations.
But it could be a more sand grain in the immense machinery that is the CMNUCC.
We hope it is not so.
Whatever it is, it is indispensable to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the rest of the EU countries.
But, in particular, France could make the discussions on gambling bets in relation to long-term financing advance (an other essential chapter that is currently being discussed): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its attitude to become as progressive in this matter as it is with others.
Therefore, we have the hope of the new Environment Minister, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
