Advertisements on pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old child injects 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published on Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the former movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results “do not have a significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problematics treated,” acquired in Oise and Paris supermarkets between July and September the foods that a 10-year-old child usually consumes in four meals and a tentempié a day.
These meals taken as a model, which comply with the official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as the golosins, were examined in the laboratories in search of chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or likely cancer agents and five are classified as safe cancer agents, as well as 37 are likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies from various institutions such as the International Center for Research on Cancer.
“While, in practically the whole of the cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumers’ exposure to potentially cancer-genic and/or PE contaminants is worrying,” the association says.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea contain by themselves more than a dozen possible cancer waste and three considered safe cancer agents, as well as about a dozen waste that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as tentempié for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide prohibited in France.
The same applies to green Jews in Kenya, including in food, in which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the Russian filet, lawn tuna and even the bread bar or chicle were adhered with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the water of the grape, the analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chlorform.
At dinner, the salmon roll was the most “nutritive” with 34 chemical waste detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk that these “contaminant cocktails” generate for the consumer “probably is underestimated,” the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), on its part, has proposed "from the severity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop "the increase of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (AESA) indicated the presence of waste of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
